// @check
// @error-at 12:14 Type `E` is `never` (an empty type — its operands have no common values), so it has no values
// A self-referential intersection `type E = A & E` is NONSENSE — `E` is defined
// in terms of itself, so it collapses to `never`. It gets an honest, self-cycle
// message ("refers to itself inside an intersection … reduces to `never`"), NOT
// the disjoint-operands wording and NOT the old confusing "a number literal and
// a type" (PR #189 review). Like a disjoint `A & B`, the error fires at the
// alias DECLARATION regardless of use, so the `let e: E = { … }` use site below
// adds no second error — exactly ONE diagnostic. The diagnostic RANGE lands on
// the `A & E` intersection EXPRESSION (0-indexed `12:9`, the `type E = A & E`
// annotation), not the alias name or the value site.
type A = { a: string }
type E = A & E
let e: E = { a: "x" }
print(e)
